1. Box-Cox Transformation


Cryer p101

  • Box-Cox Transformation function \[ g(x) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \frac{x^\lambda - 1}{\lambda}& \mbox{ for } \lambda \ne 0 \\ \log(x) & \mbox{ for } \lambda = 0 \\ \end{array} \right. \]

  • One can show \[ \frac{x^\lambda - 1}{\lambda} \to \log(x) \hspace10mm \mbox{ as } \lambda \to 0. \]

  • Sometimes called Normalizing Transformation

  • This transformation is for positive data only.

  • If data has negative observations, add a constant.

  • You can try \(\pm 1, \pm1/2, \pm 1/3, \pm 1/4, 0\) and see if it helps.

  • To see what value of \(\lambda\) makes the observation looks most normal, you can use

    acf1 <- acf; library(TSA); acf  <- acf1  #- Load TSA package for BoxCox.ar()
    
    X <- rlnorm(1000)              # generate Log-normal data
    Find.lambda <- BoxCox.ar(X)    # Find best (most normalizing) B-C transformation parameter

    Find.lambda$mle
## [1] 0

2. Conditional Moments

  • ARMA(1,2) with mean model: \[ Y_1, \ldots, Y_n \mbox{ are the observations. }\\\\ Y_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \mu + X_t \\\\ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \phi_1 X_{t-1} + \theta_1 e_{t-1} + \theta_2 e_{t-2} + e_t \]

  • Mean and Variance of ARMA(1,2) \[ E(Y_t) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \mu \\\\ V(Y_t) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \]

  • Conditional Mean and Variance of ARMA(1,2) \[ E(Y_t | all past ) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \mu + \phi_1 X_{t-1} + \theta_1 e_{t-1} + \theta_2 e_{t-2} \\\\ V(Y_t | all past ) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \sigma^2 \]

  X  <- arima.sim(n = 500, list(ar = c(.8), ma = c(.5, .2)), sd=1.5) + 5  


  library(FitARMA)
  Gam <- TacvfARMA(phi=c(.8), theta=c(-.5, -.2)) * 1.5^2     # watch the theta sign
  Gam[1]
## [1] 15.6625
  plot(X, xlim=c(0,520))
  abline(h=5+c(-1,0,1)*1.96*sqrt(Gam[1]), col="blue", lty=2)



3. OLS, GLS and Regressing TS



OLS

From the regression model \[ \mathbf Y = \mathbf X \mathbf \beta + \mathbf \epsilon \] * Ordinary Least Square minimizes the sum of squares, \((\mathbf Y - \mathbf X \mathbf \beta )'(\mathbf Y - \mathbf X \mathbf \beta )\),

  • Which result in the estimator, \[ \hat{\mathbf \beta } = (\mathbf X' \mathbf X)^{-1} \mathbf X' \mathbf Y. \]



GLS

  • Minimizes weighted sum of squares, \[ ( \mathbf Y - \mathbf X \mathbf \beta )' \mathbf \Gamma_n^{-1} (\mathbf Y - \mathbf X \mathbf \beta ) \]

  • \[ \hat{\mathbf \beta } \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm (\mathbf X' \mathbf \Gamma_n^{-1} \mathbf X)^{-1} \mathbf X' \mathbf \Gamma_n^{-1} \mathbf Y. \]

  • If \(\mathbf X\) is non-random, we have \(E( \hat{\mathbf \beta}) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \mathbf \beta\) and \[ V (\hat{\mathbf \beta }) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm (\mathbf X' \mathbf X)^{-1} \mathbf X' \mathbf \Sigma \mathbf X (\mathbf X' \mathbf X)^{-1} . \]

  • For OLS, \(\mathbf \Sigma = \sigma^2 \mathbf I\), and \[ V (\hat{\mathbf \beta }) = \sigma^2 (\mathbf X' \mathbf X)^{-1} . \]

  • For GLS, \(\mathbf \Sigma = \mathbf \Gamma_n\), and \[ V (\hat{\mathbf \beta }) = (\mathbf X' \mathbf \Gamma_n^{-1} \mathbf X)^{-1} . \] It can be shown that GLS estimator is the best linear unbiased estimator of \(\mathbf \beta\). Therefore, GLS is better than OLS, but we need \(\mathbf \Gamma_n\).



Iterative Regression Scheme

  • Compute OLS. Get residuals.

  • Fit ARMA model to the residuals by Gaussian Maximum Likelihood.

  • Using the fitted model, calculate \(\mathbf \Gamma_n\). Go back to the original series, compute GLS.

  • Repeat from 2.



Ex: OLS and GLS

  D  <- read.csv("http://gozips.uakron.edu/~nmimoto/pages/datasets/gtemp.csv")
  X  <- ts(D, start=c(1880), freq=1)
  plot(X, type='o')

  Reg1 <- lm(X~ time(X));  summary(Reg1)
  plot(Reg1$residuals)

  library(forecast)
  Fit1 <- auto.arima(Reg1$residuals)
  Fit1$coef

  library(nlme)
  cs1 <- corARMA(Fit1$coef, p=1,q=2)*Fit1$sigma
  Reg2 <- gls(X~t, correlation=cs1)
  Reg2
  Reg1
  Fit2 <- auto.arima(Reg2$residuals)
  Fit2
  Fit1


  cs2 <- corARMA(Fit2$coef, p=0,q=2)*Fit2$sigma
  Reg3 <- gls(X~t, correlation=cs2)
  Reg3
  Reg1
  Fit3 <- auto.arima(Reg3$residuals)
  Fit3
  
  Fit1

  Randomness.test(Fit3$residuals)


4. Regressing TS to TS


Sometimes, you want to model your TS lniarly dependaent on other time series.

  • Sales depends on Global Economy

  • Utility Demand depends on Temparature

  • Level of toxin depends on local industory production

  • In that case, your Model is that the time series of interest \(X_t\), has linear relstionship with your independent series \(B_t\), plus stationary noise. In the vector notation, \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \mathbf \beta \mathbf B_t + Y_t \\ Y_t \sim ARMA \] where \(x_t\) contains the explanatory TS.

  • In scalar notation, \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm a + b B_t + Y_t \hspace10mm Y_t \sim ARMA \] where \(x_t\) contains the explanatory TS.



Ex: Sales Data and Indicator

  #- Indicator and Sales -
